Bike Rental Data Analysis¶

For this exam, you will be building a model to predict the number of bikes rented in a major city in a given hour.

The "bikerental.csv" data set consists of the following variables:

  • Rented.Bike.Count: number of bikes rented (one hour)
  • Temperature: Temperature in Celsius
  • Humidity: Percent humidity
  • Wind.speed: Wind Speed (m/s)
  • Visibility: 10m visibility
  • Dew.Point.Temperature: Dew Point Temperature in Celsius
  • Solar.Radiation: Solar Radiation measured in (MJ/m^2)
  • Rainfall: Rainfall in mm (one hour)
  • Snowfall: Snowfall in cm (one hour)
  • Season: spring, summer, autumn, winter
  • Holiday: yes/no
  • Time: morning, afternoon, evening, night

Read the data and answer the questions below. Assume a significance threshold of 0.05 for hypothesis tests unless stated otherwise.

In [3]:
# Read the data set
bike = read.csv('bikerental.csv',header=TRUE)
#Set variables as categorical
bike$Seasons<-as.factor(bike$Seasons)
bike$Holiday<-as.factor(bike$Holiday)
bike$Time<-as.factor(bike$Time)

Question 2 - ANOVA¶

Create an ANOVA model called anovamodel to compare the mean Rented.Bike.Count among the different times of day. Display the corresponding ANOVA table.

In [6]:
#Code to create and display ANOVA table

anovamodel <- aov(Rented.Bike.Count~Time, data=bike)

A) Identify the value of the sum of square treatments (SSTr) from the ANOVA table.

Response to Question 2A:

The sum of square treatments is identified as: 7.453e+08.

B) Provide the formula that is used to calculate F-value in the table. Given this value, is the between-group variability greater than the within-group variability? Explain.

Response to Question 2B: F-Value = Between Group Variability (MSSTr) / Within-in Group Variability (MSE) = 248423374 / 324678 = 765.1

Yes - the bewteen-group variability is greater than the within-group variability because the F-value is large.

Question 3 - Test of Equal Means¶

A) State the null and alternative hypotheses for the test of equal means across different times of day.

Response to Question 3A

$H_0$: The mean count of rentals is the same across different times of day.

$H_A$: At least one of the means is different.

B) Do you reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis of the test of equal means at a significance level of $\alpha = 0.05$? Explain your answer using the values from the ANOVA table.

Response to Question 3B

We reject the null hypothesis that all of the means are equal because the p-value ($\approx$0) is less than the $\alpha$ value of 0.05.

C) Given your answer in part B, explain what this conclusion means in the context of the problem.

Response to Question 3C

At least one of the time periods throughout the day is different than the others in terms of count of bike rentals.

Question 6 - Residual Analysis¶

Perform residual analysis on the lm.temp model for the 4 assumptions of a simple linear regression model. State whether each assumption holds and why you came to the conclusion.

In [14]:
# Code for plots

plot(y=bike$Rented.Bike.Count, x=bike$Temperature)

plot(lm.temp$fitted, lm.temp$residuals)

hist(lm.temp$residuals,main="Histogram of residuals",xlab="Residuals")

qqnorm(lm.temp$residuals, main='QQ-Plot of Residuals')
qqline(lm.temp$residuals)

Response to Question 6

Linearity Assumption:

Based off the scatterplot the linearity assumption does not hold. A transformation may be necessary in this case.

Constant Variance Assumption and Independence:

Based off the plot of residuals with fitted values, the constant variance assumption does not hold. There does not seem to be clusters of data in the plot; therefore the independence assumption holds.

Normality Assumption:

The histogram has is slightly skewed and the q-q plot displays significant deviations at the tail ends. Therefore the normality assumption does not hold.

Response to Question 7A:

The $\lambda$ value rounded to nearest half integer is 0.5.

B) What transformation of the response variable does this lambda value suggest?

Response to Question 7B:

Given a lambda of 0.5, the suggested transformation for the response variable is square root.

Response to Question 9A

$H_0$: The coefficients of visibility and Dew.point.temperature are equal to 0.

$H_A$: At least one of the coefficients of visibility and Dew.point.temperatures is not equal to 0.

The p-value of the partial F-test is 0.216 which is greater than 0.05. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the coefficients of visibility and Dew.point.temperature are equal to 0.

B) Do the variables Visibility and/or Dew.point.temperature add statistically significant explanatory power to the model, given all other predictors are included in the model? (yes or no should be sufficient if you fully answered Part A)

Response to Question 9B

No

C) Regardless of your answer to 9B), are there any circumstances where we might want to keep variables that do not add statistically significant explanatory/predictive power to the model? Explain your answer.

Response to Question 9C

Yes there are cases when we may want to keep these variables. We may be able to use them as controlling variables to reduce bias and capture mroe meaningful results.
